<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">john_tent</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">I have been following the boards for a while now and still have a few questions as to how items are tracked by Verant. While most agree that there is some type of Database that keeps track of item transfers, the specifics seem to be unknown<P>Hence if you have answers to these question feel free to reply.<P>1.	Items, do they have a specific number that makes them unique. <BR>I.e. A blue diamond has number 30000004 and another blue diamond has 30000012? If no, does that apply for all items, or do the more rare or ueber items have unique numbers? In a very recent post somebody said that was not the case, but again, it was only one person who said that.<P>2.	How are items kept track of?<BR>Is there a record per character or per item? ( Without a specific number system it would make more sense that it was kept per person) <BR>I.e. Record “KING” entry 1. Looted a “diamond”<BR>      Record “ FRIEND” entry 1. Received a “diamond from character “KING”<BR> 	Record “KING” entry 2. Traded diamond to “FRIEND”<P>3.	Is the zone and time items were traded/dropped part of the record? <BR>I would assume yes but anybody know for sure?<BR>4.	If I drop a “DIAMOND” with ”CHARACTER A” and pick up the same “DIAMOND” with “CHARACTER B”, can Verant search the database by checking where CHARACTER A dropped the “DIAMOND” and then do a search as to who picked up the “DIAMOND”. ( If they log time and zone, it will narrow down the search, especially on rare items that probably weren’t dropped on the ground in that zone for a long time)<P>Now I am sure most people are convinced everything is logged, however 2 things make me not so sure.<P>Not being a coder I don’t know how much stress such log keeping would put on a system, but with thousands of players and millions of transaction, it seems the demand would be very excessive. Therefore it might not warrant the extra cost of keeping such an elaborate database in operation.<P>Finally, if they do keep track of everything, have records and proof of all the transactions, how come that it seems like they do not actually use the data in item disputes? If you don’t bitch enough you don’t get what you lost even if you did really lose the item. However if you make yourself a serious pain you do get your way. And from what I have read and heard I believe that to be the case even if the item never existed.<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">D23</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">There are no individual numbers or tracking associated with the items.<P>A blue diamond is item number 1998382 for example. ALL blue diamonds are that number. If anyone has a blue diamond on them, it is the database representation of the master item.<P>I am not sure if it is per person or per zone, but it is definately not per item.<P>The reason they do not go back and check the logs is it is difficult and would take "too much time" (IMO) even though it might take 30 minutes to find out the details, that is 30 minutes that they could have told another 20 people that "I am sorry, I cannot help you in this matter, there is nothign I can do"<P>If they REALLY want to, just about anything can be found out that happened in the game.<BR></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
